Downloading R and R Studio:

If you are using your own, personal computer, you will need to download and install R and RStudio. Follow the instructions here to do so (be sure to choose the correct operating system, and 64-bit R if possible/compatible): [https://www.rstudio.com/products/rstudio/download/]

Once you get RStudio open, download the Homework01.Rmd file from Blackboard and open it in RStudio (File / Open). We recommend using the Homework01.Rmd file on Blackboard as a template for your submission. If you do, be sure to delete all of the problem statements and additional text, as these are not necessary to include in your submission.

Notice how the text you write in the .Rmd file shows up in the output file each time you click Knit HTML.

For more tips/tricks on how to format things in R Markdown, go to [https://www.rstudio.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/rmarkdown-cheatsheet.pdf]

Customizing the RStudio User Interface:

The first thing youll notice is that, in the RStudio window, there are several panes that contain various things (Console, Help, Environment, History, Plots, etc).

If youre using Mac, go to RStudio / Preferences / Pane Layout. If youre using Windows, go to Tools / Global Options. Change the menu options to arrange the panes as you see fit.

In your answer to this problem, describe your chosen Pane Layout and give a brief explanation for why you chose this.

Personally, Sam prefers to have:

  • Source in its own pane on the top-right-hand side
  • Console in its own pane on the top-left-hand side of the window
  • Help and Git on the bottom-right
  • Everything else on the bottom-left

Click Apply. Now click Appearance and choose an appropriate font, font size, and theme. I personally prefer a fixed-width font like Courier.

Click Apply and okay. Finally, when coding, I prefer to minimize the bottom-left and bottom-right panes so that I have more vertical space to see the code Im writing and the output its generating. Im also okay with swapping the Source and Console windows above, though this obviously is up to you.

Problem 2

Critiquing Graphs:

Find a graph from the internet (last 7 days e.g.a news article, blog post, etc) or from an academic journal (last 60 days). Describe and critique your graph:

  1. (5 points) Include the graph in your assignment. Two choices here: (1) embed the graph/image in the .html file (see below for instructions) and submit it along with your other files on Blackboard, or (2) include a link to the graph in your answer to this question.
  2. (5 points) Describe the graph. What does the graph show? What variables are plotted on the axes, via color, or via other features of the graph?
  3. (5 points) Critique the graph. Does the graph do a good job of achieving its goals? Does the graph use an unnecessary amount of data ink? Does the graph distort the actual effect/data/relationship? What are the strengths and weaknesses (if any) of the graphic? What would you change (if anything) about this graphic?
  4. (5 points) Critique the caption and/or surrounding text. Does the text enhance the users understanding of the graphic? What else would you include in the caption/surrounding text to help the viewer understand the graphic?

Problem 3

Writing R Functions and Working with Vectors:

Read section 5 of Wassermans R Intro document on Blackboard about writing functions in R. Functions help us reuse code and enhance the reproduciblity of our code.

  1. (5 points) Write an R function called quadratic that computes the quadratic formula. That is, write a function that has four inputs a, b, c, and x and returns the quantity \(ax^2 + bx + c\).

  2. (2 points) Test your function out and demonstrate that it works for at least there different combinations of the parameters.

  3. (2 points) Type quadratic(x=2) into your code block. What happens when you only specify one argument? (Note: When knitting your document for submission, comment this line of code out, so that it does not produce an error.)

  4. (2 points) Create a new function, quadratic2, that has default values for a=1, b=1, and c=1. Type quadratic2(x=2) into your code block. What happens when you only specify one argument?

  5. (2 points) Type 1:10 at the command line in R. What happens?

  6. (2 points) What happens when you call the function with the following input: quadratic2(x = 1:10). Why does this happen?

  7. (5 points) Type plot(1:10, quadratic2(x=1:10)) into your code block. Describe the graph that shows up.

Problem 4

Introduction to ggplot2:

In R, there are several libraries or packages/groups of programs that are not permanently stored in R. One that will be particularly useful in our class is called ggplot2.

  1. (2 points) Type library(ggplot2) at the command line. Is the ggplot2 package installed on your computer? If not, type install.packages("ggplot2"), then repeat the library(ggplot2) command above.

  2. (2 points) The Comprehensive R Archive Network, or CRAN, stores most publicly accessible, open-source R packages for anyone to use. Find CRANs documentation on the ggplot2 package (e.g.by searching ggplot2 in R on the internet). You should find a PDF document that has 197 pages of documentation about ggplot2. What does the gg in ggplot2 stand for?

  3. (2 points) Who are the authors of the ggplot2 package? Who is the maintainer of the ggplot2 package? Search this persons name on the internet. What are some other R packages this person has written?

  4. (2 points) Type library(datasets). Load the trees dataset into R by typing data(trees). Type head(trees) to view the first few rows of this dataset. How many columns does the dataset have? What are the names of the columns?

  5. (12 points) Make your first ggplot2 graphic:

    • Type my.plot <- ggplot(data = trees, aes(x = Girth, y = Height)). This will create the graph object.
    • Type my.plot <- my.plot + geom_point(data = trees, aes(colour = Volume), size = 4). This will add points to the graph object, colored by Volume.
    • Type my.plot <- my.plot + ggtitle("Title Here") + labs(x = "x axis label here", y = "y axis label here")
    • Change the above code to give the graph an informative title and informative axis labels. Include units in the axis labels if possible. See help(trees) for more information about the units.
    • Critique your own graph. What do you like? What do you dislike? What would you change in the future?
    • Is there any unnecessary data ink used in this graph?
